# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-spark
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Apache Spark has its architectural foundation in the resilient distributed dataset (RDD), a read-only multiset of data items distributed over a cluster of machines, that is maintained in a fault-tolerant way.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The Dataframe API was released as an abstraction on top of the RDD, followed by the Dataset API.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] In Spark 1.x, the RDD was the primary application programming interface (API), but as of Spark 2.x use of the Dataset API is encouraged even though the RDD API is not deprecated.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The RDD technology still underlies the Dataset API.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark's RDDs function as a working set for distributed programs that offers a (deliberately) restricted form of distributed shared memory.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Inside Apache Spark the workflow is managed as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Nodes represent RDDs while edges represent the operations on the RDDs.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark facilitates the implementation of both iterative algorithms, which visit their data set multiple times in a loop, and interactive/exploratory data analysis, i.e., the repeated database-style querying of data.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The latency of such applications may be reduced by several orders of magnitude compared to Apache Hadoop MapReduce implementation.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Among the class of iterative algorithms are the training algorithms for machine learning systems, which formed the initial impetus for developing Apache Spark.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Apache Spark requires a cluster manager and a distributed storage system.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] For cluster management, Spark supports standalone native Spark, Hadoop YARN, Apache Mesos or Kubernetes.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] A standalone native Spark cluster can be launched manually or by the launch scripts provided by the install package.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] It is also possible to run the daemons on a single machine for testing.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] For distributed storage Spark can interface with a wide variety of distributed systems, including Alluxio, Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), MapR File System (MapR-FS), Cassandra, OpenStack Swift, Amazon S3, Kudu, Lustre file system, or a custom solution can be implemented.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark also supports a pseudo-distributed local mode, usually used only for development or testing purposes, where distributed storage is not required and the local file system can be used instead; in such a scenario, Spark is run on a single machine with one executor per CPU core.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark Core is the foundation of the overall project.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] This interface mirrors a functional/higher-order model of programming: a "driver" program invokes parallel operations such as map, filter or reduce on an RDD by passing a function to Spark, which then schedules the function's execution in parallel on the cluster.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] These operations, and additional ones such as joins, take RDDs as input and produce new RDDs.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] RDDs are immutable and their operations are lazy; fault-tolerance is achieved by keeping track of the "lineage" of each RDD (the sequence of operations that produced it) so that it can be reconstructed in the case of data loss.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] RDDs can contain any type of Python, .NET, Java, or Scala objects.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Besides the RDD-oriented functional style of programming, Spark provides two restricted forms of shared variables: *broadcast variables* reference read-only data that needs to be available on all nodes, while *accumulators* can be used to program reductions in an imperative style.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] A typical example of RDD-centric functional programming is the following Scala program that computes the frequencies of all words occurring in a set of text files and prints the most common ones.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Each map, flatMap (a variant of map) and reduceByKey takes an anonymous function that performs a simple operation on a single data item (or a pair of items), and applies its argument to transform an RDD into a new RDD.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] PySpark is the Python API for Apache Spark, introduced in Spark 0.7, released in February 2013.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] It allows Spark applications to be written in Python and provides an interactive shell for exploratory analysis.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] PySpark code executes under the standard CPython runtime and can call native Python libraries such as NumPy and SciPy; communication between Python user code and Spark's JVM-based core has historically been mediated by the Py4J library.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] PySpark provides Python interfaces to most of Spark's components, including Spark Core, Spark SQL and the DataFrame API, Structured Streaming, and MLlib; since Spark 4.1 it also exposes the Spark Declarative Pipelines API.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] A pandas-compatible API, known as *pandas API on Spark*, was integrated into PySpark in Apache Spark 3.2.0, released in October 2021.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] It provides equivalents to the pandas data-analysis API that execute against the Spark engine, allowing pandas-style code to be run on distributed data.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The component originated as Koalas, a separate project open-sourced by Databricks in 2019, which was subsequently merged into PySpark.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] PySpark also provides a client for Spark Connect, a client–server architecture that enables remote connectivity to Spark clusters from PySpark applications.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark SQL is a component on top of Spark Core that introduced a data abstraction called DataFrames, which provides support for structured and semi-structured data.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark SQL provides a domain-specific language (DSL) to manipulate DataFrames in Scala, Java, Python or .NET.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] It also provides SQL language support, with command-line interfaces and ODBC/JDBC server.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Although DataFrames lack the compile-time type-checking afforded by RDDs, as of Spark 2.0, the strongly typed DataSet is fully supported by Spark SQL as well.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark Declarative Pipelines (SDP) is a declarative framework for defining and running extract, transform, load (ETL) data pipelines, added in Apache Spark 4.1.0, which was released on December 16, 2025.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Developers declare the datasets a pipeline should produce and the queries that define them, rather than writing imperative code specifying how each dataset is computed and in what order; Spark constructs a dataflow graph and manages dependency ordering, parallelism, checkpointing, and retries.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The framework extends Spark's lazy, declarative execution model, previously applied to individual queries through Spark SQL, to pipelines spanning multiple datasets.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Pipelines are defined in SQL or Python and are organized around streaming tables and materialized views, with the underlying transformations expressed as "flows"; batch and streaming computations can be combined within a single pipeline.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark Structured Streaming uses Spark Core's fast scheduling capability to perform streaming analytics.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] It ingests data in micro-batches and performs RDD transformations on those micro-batches of data.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] This design enables the same set of application code written for batch analytics to be used in streaming analytics, thus facilitating easy implementation of lambda architecture.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] However, this convenience comes with the penalty of latency equal to the mini-batch duration.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Other streaming data engines that process event by event rather than in micro-batches include Storm and the streaming component of Flink.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark Streaming has support built-in to consume from Kafka, Flume, Twitter, ZeroMQ, Kinesis, and TCP/IP sockets.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] In Spark 2.x, a separate technology based on Datasets, called Structured Streaming, that has a higher-level interface is also provided to support streaming.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Apache Spark 4.x added a Real-Time Mode (RTM) execution model for Structured Streaming, with the stated goal of lowering end-to-end latency to support operational and batch workloads on a single engine.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Existing Structured Streaming queries written against the DataFrame and Dataset APIs can be executed under the new mode without modification to the query.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark can be deployed in a traditional on-premises data center as well as in the cloud.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark Connect is a decoupled client–server architecture for Apache Spark that allows remote applications to connect to a Spark cluster from any environment, introduced in Apache Spark 3.4, released in April 2023.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The architecture separates the client application from the Spark driver, which historically ran in the same process; under Spark Connect, the client is a thin library that can be embedded in application servers, IDEs, notebooks and other programming environments.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Results are streamed back to the client as Apache Arrow-encoded row batches.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] PySpark support for Spark Connect was added in Spark 3.4, and Scala client support followed in Spark 3.5; additional clients for languages including Go, Swift and Rust have been developed in later releases.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] GraphX is a distributed graph-processing framework on top of Apache Spark.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Because it is based on RDDs, which are immutable, graphs are immutable and thus GraphX is unsuitable for graphs that need to be updated, let alone in a transactional manner like a graph database.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] GraphX provides two separate APIs for implementation of massively parallel algorithms (such as PageRank): a Pregel abstraction, and a more general MapReduce-style API.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Unlike its predecessor Bagel, which was formally deprecated in Spark 1.6, GraphX has full support for property graphs (graphs where properties can be attached to edges and vertices).
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Like Apache Spark, GraphX initially started as a research project at UC Berkeley's AMPLab and Databricks, and was later donated to the Apache Software Foundation and the Spark project.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Apache Spark has built-in support for Scala, Java, SQL, R, Python, and Swift with 3rd party support for the .NET CLR, Julia, and more.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark was initially started by Matei Zaharia at UC Berkeley's AMPLab in 2009, and open sourced in 2010 under a BSD license.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] In 2013, the project was donated to the Apache Software Foundation and switched its license to Apache 2.0.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] In February 2014, Spark became a Top-Level Apache Project.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Zaharia's company Databricks set a new world record in large scale sorting using Spark.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark had in excess of 1000 contributors in 2015, making it one of the most active projects in the Apache Software Foundation and one of the most active open source big data projects.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Spark 3.5.2 is based on Scala 2.13 (and thus works with Scala 2.12 and 2.13 out-of-the-box), but it can also be made to work with Scala 3.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Apache Spark is developed by a community.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The project is managed by a group called the "Project Management Committee" (PMC).
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] Feature release branches will, generally, be maintained with bug fix releases for a period of 18 months.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] For example, branch 2.3.x is no longer considered maintained as of September 2019, 18 months after the release of 2.3.0 in February 2018.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] No more 2.3.x releases should be expected after that point, even for bug fixes.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] The last minor release within a major a release will typically be maintained for longer as an “LTS” release.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] For example, 2.4.0 was released on November 2, 2018, and had been maintained for 31 months until 2.4.8 was released in May 2021.
[src:apache-spark/apache-spark] 2.4.8 is the last release and no more 2.4.x releases should be expected even for bug fixes.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-spark/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] In software engineering, **in-memory processing** is a software architecture where a database is kept entirely in random-access memory (RAM) or flash memory so that usual accesses, in particular read or query operations, do not require access to disk storage.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] This may allow faster data operations such as joins, and faster reporting and decision-making in business.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Extremely large datasets may be divided between co-operating systems as in-memory data grids.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] In-memory processing techniques are frequently used by modern smartphones and tablets to improve application performance.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] This can result in speedier app loading times and more enjoyable user experiences.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] With disk-based technology, data is loaded on to the computer's hard disk in the form of multiple tables and multi-dimensional structures that queries are run against.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Disk-based technologies are often relational database management systems (RDBMSes), often based on the structured query language (SQL), such as SQL Server, MySQL, Oracle, and many others.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] RDBMSes are designed for the requirements of transactional processing.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Using a database that supports insertions and updates as well as performing aggregations, joins (typical in BI solutions) are typically very slow.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Another drawback is that SQL is designed to efficiently fetch rows of data, while BI queries usually involve fetching of partial rows of data involving heavy calculations.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] To improve query performance, multidimensional databases or OLAP cubes – also called multidimensional online analytical processing (MOLAP) – may be constructed.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Designing a cube may be an elaborate and lengthy process, and changing the cube's structure to adapt to dynamically changing business needs may be cumbersome.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Cubes are pre-populated with data to answer specific queries, and although they increase performance, they are still not optimal for answering all ad-hoc queries.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Information technology (IT) staff may spend substantial development time on optimizing databases, constructing indexes and aggregates, designing cubes and star schemas, data modeling, and query analysis.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Reading data from the hard disk is much slower (possibly hundreds of times slower) when compared to reading the same data from RAM.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Especially when analyzing large volumes of data, performance is severely degraded.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Though SQL is a very powerful tool, arbitrary complex queries with a disk-based implementation take a relatively long time to execute and often result in bringing down the performance of transactional processing.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] In order to obtain results within an acceptable response time, many data warehouses have been designed to pre-calculate summaries and answer specific queries only.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Optimized aggregation algorithms are needed to increase performance.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] With both in-memory database and data grid, all information is initially loaded into memory RAM or flash memory instead of hard disks.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] With a data grid, processing occurs at three orders of magnitude faster than relational databases with advanced functionality such as ACID which degrade performance in compensation for the additional functionality.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] The arrival of column-centric databases, which store similar information together, allow data to be stored more efficiently and with greater compression ratios.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] This allows huge amounts of data to be stored in the same physical space, reducing the amount of memory needed to perform a query and increasing processing speed.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Many users and software vendors have integrated flash memory into their systems to allow systems to scale to larger data sets more economically.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Users query the data loaded into the system's memory, thereby avoiding slower database access and performance bottlenecks.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] This differs from caching, a very widely used method to speed up query performance, in that caches are subsets of very specific pre-defined organized data.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] With in-memory tools, data available for analysis can be as large as a data mart or small data warehouse which is entirely in memory.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] This can be accessed quickly by multiple concurrent users or applications at a detailed level and offers the potential for enhanced analytics and for scaling and increasing the speed of an application.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Theoretically, the improvement in data access speed is 10,000 to 1,000,000 times compared to the disk.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] It also minimizes the need for performance tuning by IT staff and provides faster service for end users.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Certain developments in computer technology and business needs have tended to increase the relative advantages of in-memory technology.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] A range of in-memory products provides the ability to connect to existing data sources and access to visually rich interactive dashboards.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] This allows business analysts and end-users to create custom reports and queries without much training or expertise.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Easy navigation and ability to modify queries on the fly is of benefit to many users.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Since these dashboards can be populated with fresh data, users have access to real time data and can create reports within minutes.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] In-memory processing may be of particular benefit in call centers and warehouse management.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] With in-memory processing, the source database is queried only once instead of accessing the database every time a query is run, thereby eliminating repetitive processing and reducing the burden on database servers.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] By scheduling to populate the in-memory database overnight, the database servers can be used for operational purposes during peak hours.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] With a large number of users, a large amount of RAM is needed for an in-memory configuration, which in turn affects the hardware costs.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] The investment is more likely to be suitable in situations where speed of query response is a high priority, and where there is significant growth in data volume and increase in demand for reporting facilities; it may still not be cost-effective where information is not subject to rapid change.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Security is another consideration, as in-memory tools expose huge amounts of data to end users.
[src:apache-spark/in-memory-processing] Makers advise ensuring that only authorized users are given access to the data.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Get Spark from the downloads page of the project website.
[src:apache-spark/latest] This documentation is for Spark version 4.1.2.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Spark uses Hadoop’s client libraries for HDFS and YARN.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Downloads are pre-packaged for a handful of popular Hadoop versions.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Users can also download a “Hadoop free” binary and run Spark with any Hadoop version by augmenting Spark’s classpath.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Scala and Java users can include Spark in their projects using its Maven coordinates and Python users can install Spark from PyPI.
[src:apache-spark/latest] If you’d like to build Spark from source, visit Building Spark.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Spark runs on both Windows and UNIX-like systems (e.g.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Linux, Mac OS), and it should run on any platform that runs a supported version of Java.
[src:apache-spark/latest] This should include JVMs on x86_64 and ARM64.
[src:apache-spark/latest] It’s easy to run locally on one machine — all you need is to have `java` installed on your system `PATH`, or the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable pointing to a Java installation.
[src:apache-spark/latest] When using the Scala API, it is necessary for applications to use the same version of Scala that Spark was compiled for.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Spark comes with several sample programs.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Python, Scala, Java, and R examples are in the `examples/src/main` directory.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Sample applications are provided in Python.
[src:apache-spark/latest] To run one of the Scala or Java sample programs, use `bin/run-example <class> [params]` in the top-level Spark directory.
[src:apache-spark/latest] (Behind the scenes, this invokes the more general `spark-submit` script for launching applications).
[src:apache-spark/latest] You can also run Spark interactively through a modified version of the Scala shell.
[src:apache-spark/latest] This is a great way to learn the framework.
[src:apache-spark/latest] The `--master` option specifies the master URL for a distributed cluster, or `local` to run locally with one thread, or `local[N]` to run locally with N threads.
[src:apache-spark/latest] You should start by using `local` for testing.
[src:apache-spark/latest] For a full list of options, run the Spark shell with the `--help` option.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Since version 1.4, Spark has provided an R API (only the DataFrame APIs are included).
[src:apache-spark/latest] Example applications are also provided in R.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Spark Connect is a new client-server architecture introduced in Spark 3.4 that decouples Spark client applications and allows remote connectivity to Spark clusters.
[src:apache-spark/latest] The separation between client and server allows Spark and its open ecosystem to be leveraged from anywhere, embedded in any application.
[src:apache-spark/latest] In Spark 3.4, Spark Connect provides DataFrame API coverage for PySpark and DataFrame/Dataset API support in Scala.
[src:apache-spark/latest] To learn more about Spark Connect and how to use it, see Spark Connect Overview.
[src:apache-spark/latest] The Spark cluster mode overview explains the key concepts in running on a cluster.
[src:apache-spark/latest] Spark can run both by itself, or over several existing cluster managers.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The model is a specialization of the *split-apply-combine* strategy for data analysis.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] It is inspired by the map and reduce functions commonly used in functional programming, although their purpose in the MapReduce framework is not the same as in their original forms.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] As such, a single-threaded implementation of MapReduce is usually not faster than a traditional (non-MapReduce) implementation; any gains are usually only seen with multi-threaded implementations on multi-processor hardware.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The use of this model is beneficial only when the optimized distributed shuffle operation (which reduces network communication cost) and fault tolerance features of the MapReduce framework come into play.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Optimizing the communication cost is essential to a good MapReduce algorithm.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce libraries have been written in many programming languages, with different levels of optimization.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] A popular open-source implementation that has support for distributed shuffles is part of Apache Hadoop.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The name MapReduce originally referred to the proprietary Google technology, but has since become a generic trademark.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] By 2014, Google was no longer using MapReduce as its primary *big data* processing model, and development on Apache Mahout had moved on to more capable and less disk-oriented mechanisms that incorporated full map and reduce capabilities.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Processing can occur on data stored either in a filesystem (unstructured) or in a database (structured).
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce can take advantage of the locality of data, processing it near the place it is stored in order to minimize communication overhead.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] **Shuffle:** worker nodes redistribute data based on the output keys (produced by the `map` function), such that all data belonging to one key is located on the same worker node.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] **Reduce:** worker nodes now process each group of output data, per key, in parallel.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce allows for the distributed processing of the map and reduction operations.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Maps can be performed in parallel, provided that each mapping operation is independent of the others; in practice, this is limited by the number of independent data sources and/or the number of CPUs near each source.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Similarly, a set of 'reducers' can perform the reduction phase, provided that all outputs of the map operation that share the same key are presented to the same reducer at the same time, or that the reduction function is associative.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The parallelism also offers some possibility of recovering from partial failure of servers or storage during the operation: if one mapper or reducer fails, the work can be rescheduled – assuming the input data are still available.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Map() code** – Map() is run exactly once for each *K1* key, generating output organized by key *K2*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] **"Shuffle" the Map output to the Reduce processors** – the MapReduce system designates Reduce processors, assigns the *K2* key each processor should work on, and provides that processor with all the Map-generated data associated with that key.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Reduce() code** – Reduce() is run exactly once for each *K2* key produced by the Map step.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] **Produce the final output** – the MapReduce system collects all the Reduce output, and sorts it by *K2* to produce the final outcome.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] These five steps can be logically thought of as running in sequence – each step starts only after the previous step is completed – although in practice they can be interleaved as long as the final result is not affected.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In many situations, the input data might have already been distributed ("sharded") among many different servers, in which case step 1 could sometimes be greatly simplified by assigning Map servers that would process the locally present input data.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Similarly, step 3 could sometimes be sped up by assigning Reduce processors that are as close as possible to the Map-generated data they need to process.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Map* and *Reduce* functions of *MapReduce* are both defined with respect to data structured in (key, value) pairs.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Map* function is applied in parallel to every pair (keyed by `k1`) in the input dataset.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] This produces a list of pairs (keyed by `k2`) for each call.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] After that, the MapReduce framework collects all pairs with the same key (`k2`) from all lists and groups them together, creating one group for each key.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Each *Reduce* call typically produces either one key value pair or an empty return, though one call is allowed to return more than one key value pair.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The returns of all calls are collected as the desired result list.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Thus the MapReduce framework transforms a list of (key, value) pairs into another list of (key, value) pairs.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] This behavior is different from the typical functional programming map and reduce combination, which accepts a list of arbitrary values and returns one single value that combines *all* the values returned by map.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] It is necessary but not sufficient to have implementations of the map and reduce abstractions in order to implement MapReduce.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Distributed implementations of MapReduce require a means of connecting the processes performing the Map and Reduce phases.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Other options are possible, such as direct streaming from mappers to reducers, or for the mapping processors to serve up their results to reducers that query them.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Here, each document is split into words, and each word is counted by the *map* function, using the word as the result key.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The framework puts together all the pairs with the same key and feeds them to the same call to *reduce*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Thus, this function just needs to sum all of its input values to find the total appearances of that word.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] As another example, imagine that for a database of 1.1 billion people, one would like to compute the average number of social contacts a person has according to age.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Note that in the Reduce function, C is the count of people having in total N contacts, so in the Map function it is natural to write C=1, since every output pair is referring to the contacts of one single person.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The MapReduce system would line up the 1100 Map processors, and would provide each with its corresponding 1 million input records.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The Map step would produce 1.1 billion (Y,(N,1)) records, with Y values ranging between, say, 8 and 103.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The MapReduce System would then line up the 96 Reduce processors by performing shuffling operation of the key/value pairs due to the fact that we need average per age, and provide each with its millions of corresponding input records.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The Reduce step would result in the much reduced set of only 96 output records (Y,A), which would be put in the final result file, sorted by Y.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The count info in the record is important if the processing is reduced more than one time.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] If we reduce it with file #3, we lose the count of how many records we've already seen, so we end up with an average of 9.5 contacts for a 10-year-old person ((9+10)/2), which is wrong.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Software framework architecture adheres to open-closed principle where code is effectively divided into unmodifiable *frozen spots* and extensible *hot spots*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The frozen spot of the MapReduce framework is a large distributed sort.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *input reader* divides the input into appropriate size 'splits' (in practice, typically, 64 MB to 128 MB) and the framework assigns one split to each *Map* function.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *input reader* reads data from stable storage (typically, a distributed file system) and generates key/value pairs.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] A common example will read a directory full of text files and return each line as a record.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Map* function takes a series of key/value pairs, processes each, and generates zero or more output key/value pairs.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The input and output types of the map can be (and often are) different from each other.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] If the application is doing a word count, the map function would break the line into words and output a key/value pair for each word.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Each output pair would contain the word as the key and the number of instances of that word in the line as the value.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Each *Map* function output is allocated to a particular *reducer* by the application's *partition* function for sharding purposes.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *partition* function is given the key and the number of reducers and returns the index of the desired *reducer*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] A typical default is to hash the key and use the hash value modulo the number of *reducers*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Between the map and reduce stages, the data are *shuffled* (parallel-sorted / exchanged between nodes) in order to move the data from the map node that produced them to the shard in which they will be reduced.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The shuffle can sometimes take longer than the computation time depending on network bandwidth, CPU speeds, data produced and time taken by map and reduce computations.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The input for each *Reduce* is pulled from the machine where the *Map* ran and sorted using the application's *comparison* function.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The framework calls the application's *Reduce* function once for each unique key in the sorted order.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Reduce* can iterate through the values that are associated with that key and produce zero or more outputs.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In the word count example, the *Reduce* function takes the input values, sums them and generates a single output of the word and the final sum.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Output Writer* writes the output of the *Reduce* to the stable storage.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Properties of monoids are the basis for ensuring the validity of MapReduce operations.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In the Algebird package a Scala implementation of Map/Reduce explicitly requires a monoid class type .
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The operations of MapReduce deal with two types: the type *A* of input data being mapped, and the type *B* of output data being reduced.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Map* operation takes individual values of type *A* and produces, for each *a:A* a value *b:B*; The *Reduce* operation requires a binary operation • defined on values of type *B*; it consists of folding all available *b:B* to a single value.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] From a basic requirements point of view, any MapReduce operation must involve the ability to arbitrarily regroup data being reduced.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The second property guarantees that, when parallelized over multiple nodes, the nodes that don't have any data to process would have no impact on the result.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] These two properties amount to having a monoid (*B*, •, *e*) on values of type *B* with operation • and with neutral element *e*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] There's no requirements on the values of type *A*; an arbitrary function *A* → *B* can be used for the *Map* operation.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] This means that we have a catamorphism *A** → (*B*, •, *e*).
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Here *A** denotes a Kleene star, also known as the type of lists over *A*.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The *Shuffle* operation per se is not related to the essence of MapReduce; it's needed to distribute calculations over the cloud.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] It follows from the above that not every binary *Reduce* operation will work in MapReduce.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce programs are not guaranteed to be fast.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The main benefit of this programming model is to exploit the optimized shuffle operation of the platform, and only having to write the *Map* and *Reduce* parts of the program.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In practice, the author of a MapReduce program however has to take the shuffle step into consideration; in particular the partition function and the amount of data written by the *Map* function can have a large impact on the performance and scalability.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Additional modules such as the *Combiner* function can help to reduce the amount of data written to disk, and transmitted over the network.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce applications can achieve sub-linear speedups under specific circumstances.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] When designing a MapReduce algorithm, the author needs to choose a good tradeoff between the computation and the communication costs.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Communication cost often dominates the computation cost, and many MapReduce implementations are designed to write all communication to distributed storage for crash recovery.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In tuning performance of MapReduce, the complexity of mapping, shuffle, sorting (grouping by the key), and reducing has to be taken into account.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The amount of data produced by the mappers is a key parameter that shifts the bulk of the computation cost between mapping and reducing.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Reducing includes sorting (grouping of the keys) which has nonlinear complexity.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Hence, small partition sizes reduce sorting time, but there is a trade-off because having a large number of reducers may be impractical.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The influence of split unit size is marginal (unless chosen particularly badly, say <1MB).
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The gains from some mappers reading load from local disks, on average, is minor.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] For processes that complete quickly, and where the data fits into main memory of a single machine or a small cluster, using a MapReduce framework usually is not effective.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Since these frameworks are designed to recover from the loss of whole nodes during the computation, they write interim results to distributed storage.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] This crash recovery is expensive, and only pays off when the computation involves many computers and a long runtime of the computation.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] A task that completes in seconds can just be restarted in the case of an error, and the likelihood of at least one machine failing grows quickly with the cluster size.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] On such problems, implementations keeping all data in memory and simply restarting a computation on node failures or —when the data is small enough— non-distributed solutions will often be faster than a MapReduce system.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce achieves reliability by parceling out a number of operations on the set of data to each node in the network.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Each node is expected to report back periodically with completed work and status updates.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] If a node falls silent for longer than that interval, the master node (similar to the master server in the Google File System) records the node as dead and sends out the node's assigned work to other nodes.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Individual operations use atomic operations for naming file outputs as a check to ensure that there are not parallel conflicting threads running.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] When files are renamed, it is possible to also copy them to another name in addition to the name of the task (allowing for side-effects).
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The reduce operations operate much the same way.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Because of their inferior properties with regard to parallel operations, the master node attempts to schedule reduce operations on the same node, or in the same rack as the node holding the data being operated on.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] This property is desirable as it conserves bandwidth across the backbone network of the datacenter.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Implementations are not necessarily highly reliable.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] For example, in older versions of Hadoop the *NameNode* was a single point of failure for the distributed filesystem.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Moreover, the MapReduce model has been adapted to several computing environments like multi-core and many-core systems, desktop grids, multi-cluster, volunteer computing environments, dynamic cloud environments, mobile environments, and high-performance computing environments.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] At Google, MapReduce was used to completely regenerate Google's index of the World Wide Web.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] It replaced the old *ad hoc* programs that updated the index and ran the various analyses.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Development at Google has since moved on to technologies such as Percolator, FlumeJava and MillWheel that offer streaming operation and updates instead of batch processing, to allow integrating "live" search results without rebuilding the complete index.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce's stable inputs and outputs are usually stored in a distributed file system.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The transient data are usually stored on local disk and fetched remotely by the reducers.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] David DeWitt and Michael Stonebraker, computer scientists specializing in parallel databases and shared-nothing architectures, have been critical of the breadth of problems that MapReduce can be used for.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] They called its interface too low-level and questioned whether it really represents the paradigm shift its proponents have claimed it is.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] They challenged the MapReduce proponents' claims of novelty, citing Teradata as an example of prior art that has existed for over two decades.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Greg Jorgensen wrote an article rejecting these views.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] Jorgensen asserts that DeWitt and Stonebraker's entire analysis is groundless as MapReduce was never designed nor intended to be used as a database.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] DeWitt and Stonebraker have subsequently published a detailed benchmark study in 2009 comparing performance of Hadoop's MapReduce and RDBMS approaches on several specific problems.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] They concluded that relational databases offer real advantages for many kinds of data use, especially on complex processing or where the data is used across an enterprise, but that MapReduce may be easier for users to adopt for simple or one-time processing tasks.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The MapReduce programming paradigm was also described in Danny Hillis's 1985 thesis intended for use on the Connection Machine, where it was called "xapping/reduction" and relied upon that machine's special hardware to accelerate both map and reduce.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The dialect ultimately used for the Connection Machine, the 1986 StarLisp, had parallel `*map` and `reduce!!`, which in turn was based on the 1984 Common Lisp, which had non-parallel `map` and `reduce` built in.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The tree-like approach that the Connection Machine's hypercube architecture uses to execute `reduce` in $O(\log n)$ time is effectively the same as the approach referred to within the Google paper as prior work.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In 2010 Google was granted what is described as a patent on MapReduce.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The patent, filed in 2004, may cover use of MapReduce by open source software such as Hadoop, CouchDB, and others.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In *Ars Technica*, an editor acknowledged Google's role in popularizing the MapReduce concept, but questioned whether the patent was valid or novel.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] In 2013, as part of its "Open Patent Non-Assertion (OPN) Pledge", Google pledged to only use the patent defensively.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] The patent is expected to expire on 23 December 2026.
[src:apache-spark/mapreduce] MapReduce tasks must be written as acyclic dataflow programs, i.e. a stateless mapper followed by a stateless reducer, that are executed by a batch job scheduler.
